# Assingment 5 - Carl Holmberg

## Method

I started by building a three dimensional where each element is a list containing the atoms that are in this 1x1x1 volume.
When checking for collisions with the other files, the array could just be indexed in the same way, then i searched the surrounding positions for atoms that could be in the range, starting by searching the elements closest.
This reduces the amount of comparisions that needs to be made.

## Notes

My solution is off by 2 on the 1cdh-2csn case.
I could not figure out why, and I could not spend more time on this to try to figure out why.

## How to run

You need to have python and pip installed to run this program.

Install the required packages by running

```
$ pip install -r requirements.txt
```

Thereafter to run the program you just type

```
./identify_collisions.py [FILE1] [FILE2]
```

where `[FILE]` is the input file.
Make sure that you make the file runnable, in linux by writing

```
sudo chmod +x identify_collisions.py
```

Otherwise the program can be run by writing

```
python identify_collisions.py [FILE1] [FILE2]
```

or

```
python3 identify_collisions.py [FILE1] [FILE2]
```
